In unrelated news,
  [3]
 I want to talk about two risky bets related to Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s=
 criminal trial.
First, people  sometimes ask =E2=80=9Cwhy hasn=E2=80=99t Bankman-Fried take=
n a plea deal?=E2=80=9D Here, for instance,  is a claim that Bankman-Fried =
made a risky bet to go to trial rather than cutting a deal with prosecutors=
:
=E2=80=9CI wonder if it=E2=80=99s his insane views on risk. Like, he might =
just think the E.V. is there and be committed like that,=E2=80=9D one (form=
er) friend said. =E2=80=9CHe might think a 20 percent chance of zero [time]=
 is better than a 100 percent chance of 20 years.=E2=80=9D
But the actual answer is much simpler: Bankman-Fried didn=E2=80=99t take a =
plea deal because prosecutors  never offered him one, and never would. Why =
would they? They offered plea deals to everyone=C2=A0else=C2=A0in Bankman-F=
ried=E2=80=99s inner circle, to get those people to cooperate and testify a=
gainst Bankman-Fried, so they can maximize their (very good!) chances of co=
nvicting Bankman-Fried. Why would they give him=C2=A0a deal? What can he of=
fer them? =E2=80=9CI will testify against the real villain,  my ex-girlfrie=
nd Caroline Ellison=E2=80=9D? Not compelling. His best chance of getting an=
y sort of deal would have been if, like, $8 billion of customer money had v=
anished and he knew where it was. =E2=80=9CI have buried the money in a sec=
ret location and will give it all back to customers if you only give me 20 =
years,=E2=80=9D fine, that=E2=80=99s something to work with. But on the act=
ual facts he just has nothing prosecutors want.=C2=A0
Meanwhile the prosecutors are making their own fairly straightforward bet:
=09If they throw the book at him and go to trial, they will probably win. T=
he evidence seems strong, they have all of his friends testifying against h=
im, and it=E2=80=99s hard for me to imagine a jury saying =E2=80=9Cehh this=
 guy lost $8 billion of customer money but it was probably just an accident=
.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=09If they cut any sort of deal, they will increase their o=
dds of winning from, like, 99% to 100%, but they will get a lot of criticis=
m for going easy on society=E2=80=99s big crypto villain. It=E2=80=99s not =
worth it! This case is not just about sending Sam Bankman-Fried to prison; =
it is about explaining what went wrong at FTX, and about saying, with the f=
ull force of the US government, that That Was Bad. A plea deal doesn=E2=80=
=99t send the right message.

The second bet is: Will Bankman-Fried take the stand and testify in his own=
 defense? Buddy he has  posted on Substack in his own defense; of course he=
 will testify. Bankman-Fried will talk to absolutely anyone, with no filter=
 at all, about what happened at the end of FTX. You think he won=E2=80=99t =
talk to a=C2=A0jury=C2=A0about it?
Isn=E2=80=99t it risky for him to testify? Won=E2=80=99t he be subjected to=
 withering cross-examination from well-prepared prosecutors who will trap h=
im in lies? Well! I mean, sure, probably. But if he does not testify, all t=
he jury will have is (1) the testimony of FTX customers who are like =E2=80=
=9Call our money is gone,=E2=80=9D (2) the testimony of all of his closest =
friends and colleagues testifying =E2=80=9Cyeah we stole all the money beca=
use Sam told us to=E2=80=9D and (3)=20
screenshots of FTX computer code that is like =E2=80=9CIF you_feel_like_it =
THEN steal(all.the.money).=E2=80=9D His testimony just cannot make things w=
orse! The jury is going to get the prosecutors=E2=80=99 story and it is rea=
lly, really, really, really bad for Bankman-Fried. He needs to tell his sid=
e of the story to have any shot at all. If his testimony has a 10% chance o=
f being compelling and a 90% chance of being disastrous, that is=C2=A0all u=
pside.
  [4]
=C2=A0If he does not testify, that is 100% disastrous.
Also, he has charmed people before.=C2=A0Obviously the context here is diff=
erent, and it is easier to be charmed by the world=E2=80=99s youngest self-=
made billionaire than by a criminal defendant in a fraud trial. But I think=
 the bet, in testifying, has to be that Bankman-Fried will sound better and=
 more reasonable in explaining what was going on than the prosecutors will,=
 that they will try to trip him up and fail, that he will come across as a =
reasonable but unlucky nerd and they will come across as unreasonable bulli=
es. I don=E2=80=99t think that is all that likely, but it is not a=C2=A0cra=
zy=C2=A0bet. And it=E2=80=99s better than nothing.

 =20
   =20
      Binance fund
   =20
 =20

In November 2022, after=C2=A0FTX went bankrupt, Binance, the biggest crypto=
 exchange, announced an =E2=80=9Cindustry recovery fund=E2=80=9D to do bail=
outs for crypto. Changpeng =E2=80=9CCZ=E2=80=9D Zhao, Binance=E2=80=99s fou=
nder, tweeted that the fund would =E2=80=9Chelp projects who are otherwise =
strong, but in a liquidity crisis.=E2=80=9D As Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Emily Ni=
colle  writes today, the plan was to =E2=80=9Cpull together some of the ind=
ustry=E2=80=99s biggest names and raise at least $1 billion to finance prom=
ising startups which, due to forces outside their own control, were strappe=
d for cash.=E2=80=9D
At the time, I found this plan puzzling, because I had never heard of a cry=
pto project that was =E2=80=9Cotherwise strong, but in a liquidity crisis.=
=E2=80=9D   I asked:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CHas there ever been a pure liquidity pro=
blem at a crypto firm?=E2=80=9D Crypto project that got hacked and lost all=
 its money? Sure. Crypto project whose founders ran off with all the money?=
 Sure. Crypto project whose money was all in magic beans that turned out to=
 be worthless? Sure.
But crypto project that had lots of good long-term assets that it could not=
 sell or finance quickly, and that was therefore driven into bankruptcy des=
pite having lots of value? I mean? I suppose it is still technically possib=
le that  that describes FTX, but only by accident. (It gambled customer mon=
ey on, among many worse things, a stake in artificial intelligence startup =
Anthropic that has gone up a lot in value since FTX went bankrupt.) I just =
kind of do not think that that is how crypto=C2=A0works. Compared to tradit=
ional financial assets, crypto is unusually good at being liquid (it all tr=
ades on computers around the clock) but unusually bad at being solvent (it =
often turns out to be worthless). A fund set up to solve liquidity problems=
 in crypto won=E2=80=99t end up doing much.
Today Nicolle reports that Binance=E2=80=99s fund didn=E2=80=99t end up doi=
ng much:

Not much has come of Zhao=E2=80=99s grand plan to rescue crypto. The Indust=
ry Recovery Initiative, as it was called, has deployed less than $30 millio=
n since its inception, a Bloomberg News analysis of public digital-asset wa=
llets linked to the project indicates. Only one of nine named participants =
has invested all the funds it committed. The crypto asset sector, meanwhile=
, remains starved for cash and companies are cutting jobs to stay afloat.
The quiet unwinding of the IRI is a stark reminder of crypto=E2=80=99s penc=
hant for making bold promises it doesn=E2=80=99t always deliver on. It also=
 echoes the much-diminished stature of Binance, which is facing lawsuits fr=
om two major US regulators, and of founders like Zhao, who once crisscrosse=
d the world in private jets and mingled with heads of state and celebrities=
. Bankman-Fried, who just months before FTX=E2=80=99s implosion had embarke=
d on an industry bailout of his own, is now on trial on fraud charges in Ne=
w York.

I don=E2=80=99t actually think that Zhao made any bold promises he didn=E2=
=80=99t deliver on? I think he promised to =E2=80=9Chelp projects who are o=
therwise strong, but in a liquidity crisis,=E2=80=9D and unsurprisingly the=
re weren=E2=80=99t many.

 =20
   =20
      Innovation Refunds
   =20
 =20

One thing that I  think about sometimes is that corporations are, by their =
nature, perpetual, and that this creates weird biases. People just naturall=
y expect businesses to last forever, or, rather, they think that the mark o=
f a=C2=A0successful=C2=A0business is longevity.=C2=A0You invent a product, =
you sell it, you get money, you invest in research and development, you mak=
e more products, you keep up with trends, you make money forever. Sure some=
times you fail =E2=80=94=C2=A0you invent a product but no one buys it and y=
ou shut down =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the=C2=A0goal=C2=A0is to keep selling produ=
cts forever.
But it is not obvious to me that this makes sense for every business model?=
 =E2=80=9CYou invent a product, you sell it, you get rich, you get into yac=
hts=E2=80=9D is also, in its way, a success. It seems to me that you might =
go into a business with a finite lifespan, figuring =E2=80=9Cthis business =
is good now, and will not last forever, but I will make money now and then =
I will stop.=E2=80=9D For instance
  [5]
:
=09One classic form of private equity business is to buy up declining compa=
nies, cut costs, extract as much money as possible and manage the decline. =
This is classically a private equity business because public markets do not=
 like decline: A public-company chief executive officer, paid in long-term =
stock options, is going to be tempted to do money-wasting pivots to try to =
remain relevant. And it is a business that is controversial: People get ang=
ry at private equity for this sort of managed decline, because of the bias =
that businesses should be perpetual.=09Oil? Coal? There is  a tension in th=
e energy business among (1) people who think we will eventually stop burnin=
g oil, and want oil companies to pivot to wind energy or whatever, and (2) =
people who think we will eventually stop burning oil, and want oil companie=
s to drill while the drilling is good and spend a lot of money on stock buy=
backs. There are good reasons to think that oil companies are well position=
ed to get into the clean-energy business (they have lots of capital, they u=
nderstand energy markets), but I suspect there are also bad reasons (they a=
lready have all that office space so they might as well do=C2=A0something t=
o keep going).

For a while, you could find crypto people promising that blockchains and We=
b3 would change all of this and create a new economy in which people would =
come together to do time-limited projects and then move on to other things,=
 recombining flexibly as opportunities presented themselves. Crypto did not=
 really do that.
Anyway the US government inserted an Employee Retention Credit into the tax=
 code to encourage businesses not to get rid of employees during=C2=A0Covid=
-19. The deal is that employers can get a tax credit if they=C2=A0=E2=80=9C=
paid qualified wages to some or all employees after March 12, 2020, and bef=
ore January 1, 2022,=E2=80=9D with eligibility and amounts depending on how=
 they were affected by Covid. This created a gusher of money from the US go=
vernment to thousands of businesses, but it is complicated to claim; you ne=
ed lawyers and accountants to determine and document your eligibility. And =
the gusher is, by its terms, temporary.
So a business model exists of =E2=80=9Cfigure out if businesses are eligibl=
e for the ERC, help them get it, and take a 25% cut.=E2=80=9D This could pl=
ausibly be a service that existing tax lawyers and accountants could offer =
their existing clients, but if the gusher is big and temporary enough it mi=
ght make sense for a separate company to start up to do this. That company =
would always have an expiration date =E2=80=94=C2=A0eventually every employ=
er affected in 2020 through 2022 would get their credits =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=
 for enough money it would be worth it.
One thing to think about is that, if you have a perpetual business, you wil=
l make a lot of investments in long-term reputational goods, and you=E2=80=
=99ll be careful not to mess up your reputation for short-term gains. Where=
as if you have a business with a clear and near-term expiration date, you m=
ight want to grab as much as you can right now, and won=E2=80=99t be all th=
at careful about your reputation for getting things right.
Anyway here is a Wall Street Journal article about Innovation Refunds, a le=
ading ERC promoter:

Innovation Refunds=C2=A0is down to 270 full-time workers from a peak of 1,0=
00. It has halted all its marketing and stopped much of its activity.
Innovation Refunds was one of the largest competitors in a cottage industry=
 that flooded radio and television with ads promoting the Employee Retentio=
n Credit, or ERC. The company=E2=80=99s swift rise and fall shows how quick=
ly the once-obscure Covid-era tax break became a gold mine and how the gove=
rnment=E2=80=99s efforts to fight ERC fraud are rippling through the indust=
ry.
In September, after several warnings about ERC promoters and abuse, the Int=
ernal Revenue Service said it was halting the processing of new claims and =
would give additional scrutiny to 600,000 pending requests for the credit. =
The agency has started thousands of ERC audits.
Innovation Refunds has stopped submitting new ERC claims. [Founder Howard] =
Makler said he would decide whether to resume after the IRS releases new gu=
idance. =E2=80=9COur company is pivoting,=E2=80=9D Makler said in an interv=
iew. =E2=80=9CWe are not hanging our future on returning to the ERC.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0

The details here are that the IRS is cracking down on ERC claims, and that =
Innovation Refunds was maybe a bit aggressive in making those claims:
Some accountants who have seen its work question the quality of its analysi=
s.=C2=A0Fewer than 10 Innovation Refunds clients have told the company that=
 their ERC claims are currently under audit, Makler said, and the company s=
tands behind its work.
But the big picture is, I mean, you started a company to extract money from=
 a tax program that was always set to expire: Surely the job is to extract =
the money and then shut down? =E2=80=9CInnovation Refunds has processed mor=
e than $6 billion in ERC claims, for which it could earn roughly $1.5 billi=
on in fees.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s fine, no? You don=E2=80=99t have to =E2=
=80=9Chang=C2=A0your future on returning to the ERC=E2=80=9D; you=E2=80=99v=
e got $1.5 billion for two years=E2=80=99 work. That=E2=80=99s pretty good!

 =20
   =20
      Ozempic is great for business
   =20
 =20

We   talked yesterday about a hypothetical drug, =E2=80=9Ca drug that reduc=
es consumption in general, a universal demand suppressant,=E2=80=9D which p=
uts its users into such a Zen state of contentment that they have no need f=
or other goods or services.=C2=A0This drug would have weird economic effect=
s: A pharmaceutical company could perhaps make a lot of money selling it, b=
ut lots of=C2=A0other=C2=A0companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0the companies that sell=
 consumption, that sell snacks and alcohol and airplane tickets and streami=
ng video and internet ads =E2=80=94=C2=A0would lose money. And in our world=
 of universal common ownership of the stock market, there would be a tensio=
n between a pharmaceutical company making money from this drug and costing =
its owners money as all their=C2=A0other=C2=A0portfolio companies lose busi=
ness.
This was of course inspired by Ozempic and Wegovy and=C2=A0similar new appe=
tite-suppressing drugs. But while they are=C2=A0a little=C2=A0like that hyp=
othetical drug, they aren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0really.=C2=A0For one thing, these =
drugs=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t suppress demand all that much, and to the extent t=
hey do it is mostly demand for snacks and alcohol, not for vacations or soc=
ial media posts. Realistically people on Ozempic will probably just spend l=
ess money on snacks and more money on cars or whatever.
Meanwhile, Ozempic has some good-for-business effects. A bunch of readers p=
ointed out that Ozempic might lengthen lifespans, which is good for consump=
tion: You eat fewer snacks per year, but you have more years, so maybe you =
eat more snacks overall.=C2=A0
And you probably take just as many vacations, but you burn less jet fuel ge=
tting there. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Mary Schlangenstein   reported last m=
onth:

Airlines and planemakers obsess about reducing jet-fuel consumption by cons=
tantly finding new ways to reduce aircraft weight. They may have new allies=
 in Ozempic and other similar slimming medications.
United Airlines Holdings Inc. would save $80 million a year if the average =
passenger weight falls by 10 pounds, Sheila Kahyaoglu, a Jefferies Financia=
l analyst, estimated in a report Friday. Her work was part of a broader Jef=
feries analysis of public enthusiasm for the drug and potential beneficiari=
es of its use. =E2=80=A6
Other industries seen benefiting from the growth of weight-loss drugs inclu=
de pharmaceuticals, apparel =E2=80=94 particularly athletic clothing =E2=80=
=94 and cosmetics, the Jefferies report said. A negative effect could hit r=
estaurants and some food and beverage producers if consumers shift to healt=
hier eating or stop buying some products. The high cost of the drugs could =
lower spending for things like furniture or travel, it said.

If everyone loses 30 pounds they will all have to buy new clothes, which is=
 good for the clothing business.

