  [1] This is not the only possible view. Often the best indication of a po=
sitive-expected-value trade is that, ex post, it made money. In Jack Schwag=
er=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CHedge Fund Market Wizards,=E2=80=9D Steve Clark memor=
ably says: =E2=80=9CYour job as a trader is to make the line go from bottom=
 left to top right. That=E2=80=99s it. If the line goes down too much or to=
o long, you were wrong. You can=E2=80=99t argue that the market is wrong be=
cause it is your job to predict every move in the market. You had managers =
in 2008 who lost 50 percent, and in some cases even as much as 80 percent. =
Why? Because they couldn=E2=80=99t accept they were wrong. They kept doing =
the math, and they kept saying they were right. They missed the point. Thei=
r math might have been right, but their job isn=E2=80=99t to do the math; t=
heir job is to trade what is in front of them. You had guys saying they wer=
e right, the market was wrong, and that they had billions of dollars of emb=
edded value in their portfolio. Their job isn=E2=80=99t to create billions =
of dollars of embedded value; their job is to make the line go from bottom =
left to top right.=E2=80=9D In some sense the more sophisticated analysis i=
s that your job is to take positive-expected-value bets, but there is a lot=
 to be said for the cruder analysis.


  [2] Oh fine one other thing. When we first discussed this, I thought it w=
as kind of weird for Jane Street interns to bet their $100 daily bankroll o=
n one bet with a 1% edge, but arguably I was considering the wrong bankroll=
. A reader (and former Jane Street intern) emailed to say: "The point of th=
e bet was not to push interns to be more linear in their utility function t=
han the Kelly criterion. Quite the opposite, it was to illustrate that the =
criterion is actually less risk-averse than most people=E2=80=99s natural i=
nclination: in the case of getting paid $1 to flip $100, most interns=E2=80=
=99 intuitive reaction would be to decline the bet, but if you do the math =
Kelly tells you that you should take the flip as long as you=E2=80=99re wor=
th more than $5000, which is a pretty low bar - especially when you=E2=80=
=99re paid a JS internship salary, although every year there would be someo=
ne in the room joking about negative net worth due to student loans."


  [3] This transition is ordinarily sarcastic but here it is not! Or, I mea=
n, it is sarcastic in reverse, somehow? The point is that the bets here rea=
lly are unrelated to any sort of fancy expected value math; they have obvio=
us explanations.


  [4] I am exaggerating, and obviously this is not legal advice. In particu=
lar if he gets on the stand and rubs the judge the wrong way, that could hu=
rt him at sentencing.


  [5] There is also this fun Byrne Hobart post about the maker of the Insta=
nt Pot, which went bankrupt because everybody who wanted an Instant Pot bou=
ght one, and then never had any possible need for another one, because the =
first one did the job and was well made.


