<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/32983479.262420/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDctMDkvY29tcGFuaWVzLWtlZXAtYnV5aW5nLWJhY2=
stc3RvY2s_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAxMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc=
291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMDEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2aaf5513" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> think about sometimes</a> is t=
hat corporations are, by their nature, perpetual, and that this creates wei=
rd biases. People just naturally expect businesses to last forever, or, rat=
her, they think that the mark of a=C2=A0<em>successful=C2=A0</em>business i=
s longevity.=C2=A0You invent a product, you sell it, you get money, you inv=
est in research and development, you make more products, you keep up with t=
rends, you make money forever. Sure sometimes you fail =E2=80=94=C2=A0you i=
nvent a product but no one buys it and you shut down =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the=
=C2=A0<em>goal=C2=A0</em>is to keep selling products forever.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it is not obvious to me that this makes se=
nse for every business model? =E2=80=9CYou invent a product, you sell it, y=
ou get rich, you get into yachts=E2=80=9D is also, in its way, a success. I=
t seems to me that you might go into a business with a finite lifespan, fig=
uring =E2=80=9Cthis business is good now, and will not last forever, but I =
will make money now and then I will stop.=E2=80=9D For instance<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">One classic form of private equity bus=
iness is to buy up declining companies, cut costs, extract as much money as=
 possible and manage the decline. This is classically a private equity busi=
ness because public markets do not like decline: A public-company chief exe=
cutive officer, paid in long-term stock options, is going to be tempted to =
do money-wasting pivots to try to remain relevant. And it is a business tha=
t is controversial: People get angry at private equity for this sort of man=
aged decline, because of the bias that businesses should be perpetual.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Oil? Coal? There is <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32983479.262420/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDgvb2lsLWNvbXBhbmllcy1naXZ=
lLWJhY2stdGhlLWNhc2g_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAxMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbW=
FpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMDEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb=
25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB23e42e71" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a tension in the en=
ergy business</a> among (1) people who think we will eventually stop burnin=
g oil, and want oil companies to pivot to wind energy or whatever, and (2) =
people who think we will eventually stop burning oil, and want oil companie=
s to drill while the drilling is good and spend a lot of money on stock buy=
backs. There are good reasons to think that oil companies are well position=
ed to get into the clean-energy business (they have lots of capital, they u=
nderstand energy markets), but I suspect there are also bad reasons (they a=
lready have all that office space so they might as well do=C2=A0<em>somethi=
ng </em>to keep going).</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For a while, you could find crypto people prom=
ising that blockchains and Web3 would change all of this and create a new e=
conomy in which people would come together to do time-limited projects and =
then move on to other things, recombining flexibly as opportunities present=
ed themselves. Crypto did not really do that.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway the US government inserted an <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32983479.262420/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuaXJzLmdvdi9jb3JvbmF2aXJ1cy9lbXBsb3llZS1yZXRlbnRpb24tY3JlZGl0/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB15bfd1d2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Employee Retention Credit</a> into the =
tax code to encourage businesses not to get rid of employees during=C2=A0Co=
vid-19. The deal is that employers can get a tax credit if they=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cpaid qualified wages to some or all employees after March 12, 2020, and =
before January 1, 2022,=E2=80=9D with eligibility and amounts depending on =
how they were affected by Covid. This created a gusher of money from the US=
 government to thousands of businesses, but it is complicated to claim; you=
 need lawyers and accountants to determine and document your eligibility. A=
nd the gusher is, by its terms, temporary.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So a business model exists of =E2=80=9Cfigure =
out if businesses are eligible for the ERC, help them get it, and take a 25=
% cut.=E2=80=9D This could plausibly be a service that existing tax lawyers=
 and accountants could offer their existing clients, but if the gusher is b=
ig and temporary enough it might make sense for a separate company to start=
 up to do this. That company would always have an expiration date =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0eventually every employer affected in 2020 through 2022 would get the=
ir credits =E2=80=94=C2=A0but for enough money it would be worth it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing to think about is that, if you have =
a perpetual business, you will make a lot of investments in long-term reput=
ational goods, and you=E2=80=99ll be careful not to mess up your reputation=
 for short-term gains. Whereas if you have a business with a clear and near=
-term expiration date, you might want to grab as much as you can right now,=
 and won=E2=80=99t be all that careful about your reputation for getting th=
ings right.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/32983479.262420/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9idXN=
pbmVzcy9lbnRyZXByZW5ldXJzaGlwL3RoZS1zdHVubmluZy1ib29tLWFuZC1idXN0LW9mLWEtdG=
F4LXJlZnVuZC1raW5nLTQxNjgzMGIzP21vZD1pdHBfd3Nq/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB17c=
7953c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">Wall Street Journal article</a> about Innovation Refunds, a =
leading ERC promoter:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Innovation Refunds=C2=A0is down to 270 full-ti=
me workers from a peak of 1,000. It has halted all its marketing and stoppe=
d much of its activity.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Innovation Refunds was one of the largest comp=
etitors in a cottage industry that flooded radio and television with ads pr=
omoting the Employee Retention Credit, or ERC. The company=E2=80=99s swift =
rise and fall shows how quickly the once-obscure Covid-era tax break became=
 a gold mine and how the government=E2=80=99s efforts to fight ERC fraud ar=
e rippling through the industry.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In September, after several warnings about ERC=
 promoters and abuse, the Internal Revenue Service said it was halting the =
processing of new claims and would give additional scrutiny to 600,000 pend=
ing requests for the credit. The agency has started thousands of ERC audits=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Innovation Refunds has stopped submitting new =
ERC claims. [Founder Howard] Makler said he would decide whether to resume =
after the IRS releases new guidance. =E2=80=9COur company is pivoting,=E2=
=80=9D Makler said in an interview. =E2=80=9CWe are not hanging our future =
on returning to the ERC.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The details here are that the IRS is cracking =
down on ERC claims, and that Innovation Refunds was maybe a bit aggressive =
in making those claims:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some accountants who have seen its=
 work question the quality of its analysis.=C2=A0Fewer than 10 Innovation R=
efunds clients have told the company that their ERC claims are currently un=
der audit, Makler said, and the company stands behind its work.</p></blockq=
uote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the big picture is, I mean, you started a =
company to extract money from a tax program that was always set to expire: =
Surely the job is to extract the money and then shut down? =E2=80=9CInnovat=
ion Refunds has processed more than $6 billion in ERC claims, for which it =
could earn roughly $1.5 billion in fees.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s fine, no? =
You don=E2=80=99t have to =E2=80=9Chang=C2=A0your future on returning to th=
e ERC=E2=80=9D; you=E2=80=99ve got $1.5 billion for two years=E2=80=99 work=
. That=E2=80=99s pretty good!</p>
