=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">Hedge Fund Market Wizards</a>,=E2=80=9D Steve Clark memorably =
says: =E2=80=9CYour job as a trader is to make the line go from bottom left=
 to top right. That=E2=80=99s it. If the line goes down too much or too lon=
g, you were wrong. You can=E2=80=99t argue that the market is wrong because=
 it is your job to predict every move in the market. You had managers in 20=
08 who lost 50 percent, and in some cases even as much as 80 percent. Why? =
Because they couldn=E2=80=99t accept they were wrong. They kept doing the m=
ath, and they kept saying they were right. They missed the point. Their mat=
h might have been right, but their job isn=E2=80=99t to do the math; their =
job is to trade what is in front of them. You had guys saying they were rig=
ht, the market was wrong, and that they had billions of dollars of embedded=
 value in their portfolio. Their job isn=E2=80=99t to create billions of do=
llars of embedded value; their job is to make the line go from bottom left =
to top right.=E2=80=9D In some sense the more sophisticated analysis is tha=
t your job is to take positive-expected-value bets, but there is a lot to b=
e said for the cruder analysis.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-2" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[2] Oh fine one other thing. When we first dis=
cussed this, I thought it was kind of weird for Jane Street interns to bet =
their $100 daily bankroll on one bet with a 1% edge, but arguably I was con=
sidering the wrong bankroll. A reader (and former Jane Street intern) email=
ed to say: "The point of the bet was not to push interns to be more linear =
in their utility function than the Kelly criterion. Quite the opposite, it =
was to illustrate that the criterion is actually less risk-averse than most=
 people=E2=80=99s natural inclination: in the case of getting paid $1 to fl=
ip $100, most interns=E2=80=99 intuitive reaction would be to decline the b=
et, but if you do the math Kelly tells you that you should take the flip as=
 long as you=E2=80=99re worth more than $5000, which is a pretty low bar - =
especially when you=E2=80=99re paid a JS internship salary, although every =
year there would be someone in the room joking about negative net worth due=
 to student loans."</p>
</div>
